tweet_text: thoughts from the heart     our worldview is shaped by our experiences  before you continue bookmark this post so you can come back to it whenever you need it        in 2017 i began investing in crypto at that time i had little to no understanding of bitcoin but a small stake kept me engaged until i sold for a profit  i was happy and felt smart      during the subsequent bear market i stayed out of crypto and when i wanted back in realized i was clueless many things had changed  i wasnt happy and i felt dumb     i realized i needed to be on x to stay up to date so i opened my first account in december 2020 and enjoyed the journey even though i made a lot of mistakes  i was learning  every day felt like progress     i grew my account to 14500 followers got paid by x for creating content and had different roles for different companies paying me 8000 monthtomonth    in november 2023 that account was suspended without cause or reasoning i appealed 80 times to no avail so i rejoined x with a new account  it took me until very recently to get my mind back on track  i was devasted       is it worth rebuilding what i lost would i even be able to what if it doesnt work is it worth it    my time here has taught me valuable lessons such as  how to grow and lose an audience how to persevere in difficult times how to avoid scams how to research what is truly relevant how to build a web3 business time in the market beats the market real friends  number of followers    i have learned these lessons because      i had to start from scratch twice organically had almost given up multiple times my main wallet got drained very early on my journey despite all this i kept learning i kept active i follow the right people and we grow together i research my news every single day i am building my own company i dont have fomo  think act let time favour you theres always a bigger fish thats okay i surrounded myself with real friends    i have reached 2000 followers and i feel more humbled and grateful than ever  with all confidence i say i am here to stay  reach out if you ever struggle  i am here for you

tweet_text: physical property or bitcoin theres a big mindset shift that has to take place   right now a lot of people think oh if i want to get ahead i need to buy a property not really realising the costs risks and leverage involved consider  maintenance   strata fees  property taxes  legal and conveyancing fees  real estate broker fees andor property manager fees  if youre renting it out the tenant could damage your property or not pay or you could have vacancy and no income for some part of the year   you might not see as much price appreciation as you hope  the state can change the rules on how you use the property  the neighbourhood could change over time and become worse  stacking bitcoin is actually easier and more accessible but youve gotta be willing and able to hodlstack for 4 years minimum and longer if you can   also with a 25 year mortgage youre relatively locked in to an illiquid asset that is not so easy or quick to sell if you need to consider if you did run into an emergency and needed funds with bitcoin you can sell or spend just a fraction of your stack not so easy to just sell a fraction of your house or apartment   yes bitcoin has these huge 5075 drops every few years but that is more than made up for by the overall upside if you continually stack through the cycle and hodl for long enough as of today bitcoins annual cagr compound annual growth rate on a 10 year basis is 57year yes thats including the drops every now and then   tldr stack bitcoin instead of levering up on property
tweet_raw: Physical Property or Bitcoin?Theres a big mindset shift that has to take place. Right now a lot of people think oh if I want to get ahead I need to buy a property not really realising the costs risks and leverage involved. Consider:- maintenance - strata fees- property taxes- legal and conveyancing fees- real estate broker fees and/or property manager fees- if youre renting it out the tenant could damage your property or not pay. Or you could have vacancy and no income for some part of the year. - you might not see as much price appreciation as you hope- the state can change the rules on how you use the property- the neighbourhood could change over time and become worseStacking Bitcoin is actually easier and more accessible. But youve gotta be willing and able to HODL/stack for 4 years minimum and longer if you can. Also with a 25 year mortgage youre relatively locked in to an illiquid asset that is not so easy or quick to sell if you need to. Consider if you did run into an emergency and needed funds with Bitcoin you can sell or spend just a fraction of your stack. Not so easy to just sell a fraction of your house or apartment! Yes Bitcoin has these huge 50-75% drops every few years but that is more than made up for by the overall upside if you continually stack through the cycle and HODL for long enough. As of today Bitcoins annual CAGR (Compound Annual Growth Rate) on a 10 year basis is ~57%/year. Yes thats including the drops every now and then. tl;dr stack bitcoin instead of levering up on property

tweet_raw: KASPA FRACTAL -- WE HAVE LIFTOFF!Its been a wild ride documenting the $KAS price action against the 2020 $ADA and $ETH fractals.Fractals are very speculative but the important caveat of the $ADA fractal in particular is that #Cardano has similar supply as $KAS. Why is that important? Well we can guess the future price fairly accurately this way assuming the capital inflow into $KAS pushes it to a similar market cap as $ADA at its ATH from the 2020/2021 cycle.And when it comes down to betting on capital inflow it requires conviction in relation to the fundamentals of the project. Of course all of this is speculative and highly individual and depends on what YOU find valuable and important.However given that $KAS is still the TOP PERFORMING ASSET consistently with a 12 month lookback for the last 2+ years Id say enough people are in agreement that there is something special about @KaspaCurrency on a fundamental level.It trades super cleanly obeying technical analysis likely due to its 100% fair launch no pre-sale or venture capitalists holding large swaths of coins.It completely breaks the paradigm of what was thought possible for a proof-of-work running at 1 block/second and soon 10 bps making it a completely decentralized trustless (requires no middleman) scalable currency with smart-contracts on the horizon (will allow stablecoins).The founder Yonatan Sompolinsky is one of the most cited academics in the industry and his work gave rise to many Top 20 and Top 10 projects. And like-attracts-like so knowing this should have made your job much easier.It is truly second to none is 10+ years in the making and is on the cutting edge of decentralized fintech blazing the way--#Kaspa is the real innovator and will likely be 10 steps ahead of anything else that comes along. #BTC was the first implementation of a stateless money but wasnt practical for money due to its inability to scale (too slow and expensive to transact for common daily purchases like food transportation and entertainment). $KAS shines because it possesses all the same qualities of a fair launch decentralized trustless proof-of-work protocol but with the added benefit of being fast making it like a decentralized trustless VISA with no headquarters or company behind it.This was the vision of #Bitcoin and you could say #Bitcoin was just a proving ground for something better. And maybe its @KaspaCurrency

tweet_raw: Let me correct this a bit with updated info @Justin_Bons. 1. Validator Count: (8/10) Polkadot plans to increase its validator set to 372 by mid-2024. It operates with a dynamic set of 297 validators elected daily from a pool that has seen numbers between 917 and 990. 2. Client Ecosystem Diversity: (7/10) Polkadot supports multiple client implementations including those based on Rust (the primary implementation by Parity Technologies) Go (Gossamer) and C++ (Kagome) each backed by the Web3 Foundation. This diversification enhances resilience against software vulnerabilities and network attacks showcasing a strong commitment to decentralization. However the dominance of Paritys implementation could be seen as lowering the score here; thus the score is only 7/10.3. Permissionless Nature: (10/10) Polkadots design is inherently permissionless allowing anyone to participate in the network as a validator nominator or governance participant provided they stake DOT tokens. 4. Consensus Mechanism and Delegation: (8/10) Polkadot uses Nominated Proof of Stake (NPoS) as its consensus mechanism which involves validators and nominators to secure the network. 5. On-chain Governance: (9/10) Polkadot implements the most advanced governance mechanisms including direct community involvement adaptive voting systems and integrating OpenGov for a more decentralized and inclusive decision-making process. 6. Ecosystem and Faction Diversity: (6/10) Polkadots ecosystem is vast encompassing numerous parachains developers and projects building on its platform. The governance system allows various factions within the community to have a say although the influence of certain groups or entities can still be significant. DOT total score: 48/60

tweet_text: blockchain is for normal everyday people but it must be implemented and abstracted away by entrepreneurs the sell then is that you must appeal to entrepreneurs against existing software solutions that are mostly faster cheaper and easier to use venmo stripe ach the opportunity is that those existing solutions are insufficient because they are inaccessible or incomplete in their offering for a lot of the world therefore you have to convince or attract entrepreneurs then who either a see opportunities outside their own pain or b feel the pain of jurisdictions where existing solutions lack coverage  both of those are really hard to do its tough to build a business whose services you dont need but its also difficult to attract educate and empower entrepreneurs who deeply feel the pain of the need that blockchain solves when those building the software are removed from both a and b  we need to make blockchain easy but when i say easy im not thinking about users im thinking about entrepreneurs and developers the users of our protocols vs users of their services we certainly need to understand their users and ensure were building helps for them to easily help their users but our energy would be best spent understanding the entrepreneurial opportunities and ensuring it is as easy as possible to go from discovering our tools to implementing solutions to problems where existing solutions fall short some of this will be partnerships with existing solutions to behave as a sort of extension or stop gap but i believe most of it will be new work done in partnership with entrepreneurs who feel the pain of the problems theyre trying to solve  tldr mass adoption of blockchain is the wrong target getting everyone in the world access to robust financial services is the goal and its one only blockchain can solve it will only be realized however if protocols like stellarorg make it easy to reach such a lofty objective by working closely with the entrepreneurs who feel the pain of the problem personally  by way of example the ones that come to mind are companies focused on a sort of last mile model starlink is a great example companies providing supplies for cell phone service stations in remote areas tire shops in india wind farms in kenya how are essential quality of life services provided in remote areas thats what were doing and we would do well to pay close attention to how this is and has been done by others
tweet_raw: Blockchain is for normal everyday people but it must be implemented and abstracted away by entrepreneurs. The sell then is that you must appeal to entrepreneurs against existing software solutions that are mostly faster cheaper and easier to use. (Venmo Stripe ACH) The opportunity is that those existing solutions are insufficient because they are inaccessible or incomplete in their offering for a lot of the world. Therefore you have to convince or attract entrepreneurs then who either A) see opportunities outside their own pain or B) feel the pain of jurisdictions where existing solutions lack coverage.Both of those are really hard to do. Itâ€™s tough to build a business whose services you donâ€™t need but itâ€™s also difficult to attract educate and empower entrepreneurs who deeply feel the pain of the need that blockchain solves when those building the software are removed from both A) and B).We need to make blockchain easy but when I say â€œeasyâ€ Iâ€™m not thinking about users Iâ€™m thinking about entrepreneurs and developers. The users of our protocols vs users of their services. We certainly need to understand their users and ensure weâ€™re building helps for them to easily help their users but our energy would be best spent understanding the entrepreneurial opportunities and ensuring it is as easy as possible to go from discovering our tools to implementing solutions to problems where existing solutions fall short. Some of this will be partnerships with existing solutions to behave as a sort of extension or stop gap but I believe most of it will be new work done in partnership with entrepreneurs who feel the pain of the problems theyâ€™re trying to solve.tl;dr mass adoption of blockchain is the wrong target. Getting everyone in the world access to robust financial services is the goal and itâ€™s one only blockchain can solve. It will only be realized however if protocols like @StellarOrg make it easy to reach such a lofty objective by working closely with the entrepreneurs who feel the pain of the problem personally.By way of example the ones that come to mind are companies focused on a sort of â€œlast mileâ€ model. @Starlink is a great example. Companies providing supplies for cell phone service stations in remote areas. Tire shops in India wind farms in Kenya. How are essential quality of life services provided in remote areas? Thatâ€™s what weâ€™re doing and we would do well to pay close attention to how this is and has been done by others.
